<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Committee Oversight &#151; The Committee has ultimate authority to determine, and reduce if appropriate, compensation
provided to our executive officers.</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="2%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Independent Compensation Consultant &#151; The Committee retains an outside independent compensation consultant.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Section&nbsp;162(m) and Regulatory Considerations </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Internal Revenue Code Section&nbsp;162(m) limits the deductibility of compensation in excess of $1,000,000 paid in any calendar year to certain covered executives. As a
result, compensation paid in excess of $1,000,000 in a year to our NEOs is generally not deductible. However, pursuant to the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, which allowed companies to grandfather certain performance-based compensation in excess of
$1,000,000 if in effect on or before November&nbsp;2, 2017, the Company has determined that the stock option awards (including in excess of $1,000,000) that were in effect as of such date, are intended to qualify as performance-based under the
grandfather rules. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Committee will, consistent with its past practice, continue to retain flexibility to design compensation programs that are in the best
long-term interests of the Company and our stockholders, with deductibility of compensation being one of a variety of considerations taken into account. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Committee&#146;s Independent Consultant </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Cook, the independent compensation consultant, has been retained by and reports
directly to the Committee. It also provides peer group directors&#146; compensation data to the Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee; it does not have any other consulting engagements with management or ITW. Based on its consideration of
factors under NYSE listing standards, the Committee concluded that the work performed by Cook and its senior advisor involved in the engagement did not raise any conflict of interest or independence concerns. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">39 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">These amounts include an amount of interest in the applicable calendar year considered to be in excess of market rates
credited to the deferred compensation accounts of the NEOs under the ECRIP, discussed in more detail under &#147;Nonqualified Deferred Compensation&#148; below. When a participant attains retirement eligibility at age 55 with 10 years of service,
any amounts in his or her ECRIP account deferred prior to January&nbsp;1, 2010 are entitled to a return of 130&nbsp;percent of the monthly Moody&#146;s Corporate Bond Yield Average rate, and the excess interest portion is deemed to be amounts
exceeding 100&nbsp;percent of such rate. This additional interest credit applies to all eligible plan participants, including the eligible NEOs. All amounts deferred after December&nbsp;31, 2009 accrue interest at 100&nbsp;percent of the
Moody&#146;s Rate. The individual amounts of pension benefits and excess interest credits earned in each year are shown in the table below. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">The range of potential payouts under the Performance Cash awards for the three-year period 2020 through 2022 is set forth
in these columns. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(3)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">The range of potential share distributions under the 2020 PSU awards for the NEOs as set by the Committee in February
2020 for performance for the three-year period 2020 through 2022 is set forth in these columns. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Exercise price is equal to the closing price on the grant date. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(5)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Grant date fair values of options awarded to the NEOs on February&nbsp;14, 2020 were based on an implied value of $35.45
per share as determined using a binomial valuation technique under Accounting Standards Codification Topic 718. Grant date fair value of PSUs was based on the assumption that the performance conditions will be met at target. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">42 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>

exceptions for termination upon death, disability, retirement and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(2)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">PSUs were granted in 2018, 2019, and 2020 and are subject to three-year vesting, as well as achievement of operating
margin, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">After-tax</FONT> ROIC and EPS performance goals. The number of PSUs included in this table assumes target performance is met. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_23"></A><A NAME="tx53919_62"></A>Option Exercises and Stock Vested
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><A NAME="rom_153919_71"></A>The following
table provides information regarding option exercises and stock vesting for each NEO during 2020. The value realized upon the exercise of options is calculated using the difference between the option exercise price and the market price of ITW&#146;s
common stock at the time of exercise multiplied by the number of shares underlying the option. The value realized upon the vesting of stock awards is based on the closing price of ITW&#146;s common stock on the vesting date. </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_25"></A><A NAME="tx53919_64"></A>ITW Retirement Plans </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW Retirement Accumulation Plan
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We maintain the ITW Retirement Accumulation Plan (the Pension Plan) for the benefit of eligible employees to provide a portion of the income
necessary for retirement. The Pension Plan was closed to new entrants effective January&nbsp;1, 2007. The Pension Plan is structured as a &#147;pension equity plan&#148; under which a participant accumulates an
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">age-based</FONT> percentage for each year of plan participation. The sum of the Accumulation Percentages multiplied by final average annual pay (salary and annual incentive EIP paid in the highest five years out of
the last ten complete calendar years of service), plus the sum of the Excess Percentages multiplied by the final average annual pay above the Covered Compensation, produce an amount that can be received as a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">lump-sum</FONT> payment or an actuarially equivalent lifetime annuity. For each year of credited service after December&nbsp;31, 2000, the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">age-based</FONT> percentages are as follows:
</P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(1)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Covered Compensation is a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">35-year</FONT> average of the maximum earnings recognized in
calculating Social Security benefits. For 2020, the Covered Compensation amount for an individual attaining age 65 was $86,052, while for an employee age 35 or younger it was $137,700. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Prior to 2001, the Pension Plan operated under a traditional annuity formula (a normal retirement benefit equal to 1&nbsp;percent of final average annual pay and
0.65&nbsp;percent of such pay in excess of covered compensation for each of the first 30 years of credited service plus 0.75&nbsp;percent of final average annual pay for any additional years). As part of the transition to the pension equity formula,
as of December&nbsp;31, 2000: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Accrued benefits under the traditional annuity formula were converted to an initial pension equity percentage by
calculating the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">lump-sum</FONT> value of the normal retirement annuity and dividing by the average annual pay at that time. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Participants who had 5 years of participation and whose age plus vesting service equaled at least 50 years were entitled to
additional pension equity credits of 4&nbsp;percent of final average annual pay per year for each year of employment from 2001 through 2015. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">45 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW Irish Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Irish Pension Plan operates under a traditional annuity formula (a normal retirement benefit equal to 1.5&nbsp;percent of final average annual pay for each year of
credited service). The final average annual pay is the highest consecutive pensionable base salary over any three-year period over the last ten complete years of service. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Nonqualified Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Nonqualified Pension Plan is maintained to make up for benefits that cannot be paid under the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> Pension Plan due to Internal Revenue Code limitations on the amount of compensation that may be
considered and the amount of benefit that may be paid. The Company has not considered awarding additional years of service to executive officers under the plan and, therefore, does not currently have a policy on such awards. For the most part, the
Nonqualified Pension Plan uses the same formulas and other computation elements as the Pension Plan with certain exceptions, including the following: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">The Pension Plan uses net compensation after deferrals under the Executive Contributory Retirement Income Plan (ECRIP), and
the Nonqualified Pension Plan uses total eligible compensation (generally, salary and EIP award). </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">The Nonqualified Pension Plan provides that a participant who leaves the Company, other than upon retirement, may forfeit
any plan benefits based on eligible compensation above the IRS maximum amount ($285,000 in 2020) that may be recognized under a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> plan. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:4pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="11%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="left" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">In addition to the annuity and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">lump-sum</FONT> options available under the Pension Plan, a
participant in the Nonqualified Pension Plan may elect to receive fixed monthly installments over 2 to 20 years. If the executive left employment prior to death, disability or retirement, or if the plan is terminated in conjunction with a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> the benefit from the Nonqualified Pension Plan would be paid as a lump sum. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Nonqualified Deferred Compensation </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The
Company&#146;s ECRIP offers designated executives an opportunity to defer a portion of their salary and earned <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-equity</FONT> incentive to a deferred compensation account to receive the Company contributions they
would otherwise receive if such deferrals had been made under our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> Savings and Investment Plan and IRS limits did not apply. Deferred amounts receive a rate of interest based on the monthly
Moody&#146;s Long-Term Corporate Bond Yield Average (Moody&#146;s Rate). All of the NEOs are eligible for the ECRIP. An ECRIP participant may defer from 6&nbsp;percent to 50&nbsp;percent of his or her salary and from 6&nbsp;percent to
85&nbsp;percent of his or her variable cash components (EIP and Performance Cash), with the applicable Company matching contribution on the salary and EIP amounts under the Savings and Investment Plan formula (in lieu of any matching contributions
under that plan). Salary and EIP deferrals under the ECRIP reduce the compensation that may be recognized under the Savings and Investment Plan and the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> Pension Plan. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For employees who are not eligible to participate in the pension plan due to the participation freeze on January&nbsp;1, 2007, the Company contributes a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-elective</FONT> contribution to the Savings and Investment Plan, up to the IRS Compensation Limits and continues to contribute above the IRS Compensation Limits to this plan. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">46 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">For 2020, the Social Security Wage Base was $137,700. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The ECRIP features include a maximum limit on the amount of interest under the Moody&#146;s Rate that would be recognized (12&nbsp;percent annualized, or
15.6&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible to receive 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate), a return of deferral feature whereby an individual could elect to receive a return of the principal amount deferred after a period of at least five years,
and options for payment following death, disability or retirement as a lump sum or in monthly installments over 2 to 20 years. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Retirement under the ECRIP is defined
as having attained age 55 with at least 10 years of service, or age 65 with at least 5 years of service. If an ECRIP participant&#146;s employment ends due to retirement, death, or disability, amounts deferred to the ECRIP prior to January&nbsp;1,
2010 will receive interest crediting of 130&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate. Amounts deferred to the ECRIP after December&nbsp;31, 2009 are only eligible to receive 100&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate. During 2020, the Moody&#146;s Rate
applied to ECRIP accounts ranged from 2.74&nbsp;percent to 3.42&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible for 100&nbsp;percent of the Moody&#146;s Rate, and 3.56&nbsp;percent to 4.44&nbsp;percent for amounts eligible for 130&nbsp;percent of Moody&#146;s.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">If terminated in conjunction with a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> participants would receive
their ECRIP as <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">a&nbsp;lump-sum</FONT> payment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table sets forth ECRIP account information for each NEO during fiscal
year 2020. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt"></TD></TR>
</TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">47 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<TD WIDTH="4%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(4)</TD>

<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_26"></A><A NAME="tx53919_65"></A>Potential Payments upon Termination </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:2pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our severance and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> protections are designed to be fair and competitive. These protections are intended to retain executives in the event they need to consider actions that may impact job security, and ease an
executive&#146;s transition at retirement. Providing these benefits help us compete for talent, and we believe they are fully within the range of competitive practice at similar companies. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Further, our NEOs are not covered by employment agreements and are employed &#147;at will.&#148; No payments or benefits are automatically payable to NEOs upon a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> and if there is a qualifying termination following a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT>
there are no tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-up</FONT> payments. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Payments and benefits received by NEOs upon termination are governed by the arrangements
described below and quantified at the end of this section. We have estimated the amounts involved assuming that the termination became effective as of December&nbsp;31, 2020. The actual amounts to be paid out can only be determined at the time of
the NEOs&#146; departure from the Company. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">48 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Annual Executive Incentive Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The EIP provides that if a participant is employed as of the last day of the fiscal year, he or she would receive any amounts earned under the EIP for that fiscal year.
In the event an NEO becomes permanently disabled or dies, the NEO would be eligible for a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rated</FONT> payout under the EIP. If termination of employment other than for death, disability, retirement or <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> occurs prior to the last day of the fiscal year, a participant forfeits his or her award; however, the Compensation Committee has the discretion to award an
amount prorated for the portion of the fiscal year that the participant was employed. Actual amounts earned by the NEOs based on performance in 2020 are discussed in more detail above in &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis &#151; Components
of the 2020 Executive Compensation Program &#151; Annual Executive Incentive Plan.&#148; </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>ITW Retirement Accumulation Plan and
Nonqualified Pension Plan </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs who are terminated for any reason receive their benefits under the ITW Retirement Accumulation Plan and Nonqualified
Pension Plan as described in the Pension Benefits tables above. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Executive Contributory Retirement Income Plan </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">NEOs who are terminated for any reason receive contributions and accumulated earnings as outlined in the Nonqualified Deferred Compensation section above. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Long-Term Incentive Plan Awards </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>Stock
Options</I>: In the event of a termination upon death or disability, all unvested options held by the NEOs would immediately vest. In the event of a termination upon retirement (defined as a combined age and service of 70, subject to a minimum age
of 55 and a minimum service of 5 years), 75&nbsp;percent of stock options granted within one year from the retirement date would be forfeited and the remaining would continue to vest. Additionally, stock options granted more than one year from the
retirement date would continue to fully vest. Messrs. Santi, O&#146;Herlihy, Martindale, and Hartnett meet the retirement criteria for the 2018, 2019 and 2020 awards as of December&nbsp;31, 2020. In the event of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> stock options that are not continued or replaced would fully vest and those that are continued or replaced would only vest upon involuntary termination of employment after the <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>PSUs and Performance Cash</I>: In the event of a termination upon
death or disability, the awards would vest based on the actual performance level achieved and be paid after the end of the performance period. In the event of a termination upon retirement (defined as a combined age and service of 70, subject to a
minimum age of 55 and a minimum service of 5 years), the awards would vest <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> based on date of termination and be paid after the end of the performance period. In the event of a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> an award that is not continued or replaced will fully vest on date of the
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> at the greater of target or actual achievement level and payment will be pro rata based on the number of days during the applicable performance period
before the occurrence of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> In the event of involuntary termination of employment within two years following a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> an award that has been replaced would fully vest without conditions. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For all NEOs, in the event of a
termination other than upon retirement, death, disability or a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> any unvested options, PSUs, and Performance Cash held on such date by the NEOs would be
forfeited. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Policy
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company&#146;s 2011 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Compensation
Policy provides that, upon an actual or constructive termination following a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> of the Company, the NEOs and other elected officers would be entitled to
receive: (i)&nbsp;two times annual cash compensation (base salary plus </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">49 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">
average annual incentive pay over the prior three years); (ii) a prorated amount of that year&#146;s annual incentive bonus at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater); and
(iii)&nbsp;a prorated amount of the value of Performance Cash awards at the target level (or actual achievement level if greater). Notwithstanding the foregoing, if the payments under the preceding clauses (ii)&nbsp;and (iii) were not replaced at
the time of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> then such awards will be deemed to be earned and immediately payable at the greater of target or actual achievement level pro rata
based on the number of days during the applicable performance period before the occurrence of the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> We do not gross up any of the compensation paid in
the event of termination due to a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control.</FONT></FONT> </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_27">
</A><A NAME="tx53919_66"></A>Summary of Termination and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Provisions </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The benefits for the NEOs under each termination scenario are
outlined below. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Retirement</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Involuntary</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">&nbsp;(w/o&nbsp;Cause)&nbsp;</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Death/</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">&nbsp;Disability&nbsp;</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD>

is not achieved, the award is forfeited. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left">Awards that are replaced after a
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> do not receive accelerated vesting. Double-trigger vesting occurs for awards that are continued or replaced if actual or constructive termination
occurs within two years of a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> of the Company. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="5%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">(6)</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="left"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pro-rata</FONT> vesting is at the greater of target or actual achievement level.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_28"></A><A NAME="tx53919_67"></A>Termination and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Payments and Benefits </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following table shows the value of payments and benefits that the NEOs would receive pursuant to the 2011 Long-Term Incentive Plan, the 2015 Long-Term Incentive Plan
and the 2011 <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Change-in-Control</FONT></FONT> Severance Compensation Policy upon retirement, involuntary termination without cause, death, disability or a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control,</FONT></FONT> assuming that termination occurred as of the last business day of fiscal 2020. It also shows the Company&#146;s severance benefits that would be payable to
the NEOs and that are available to employees generally. For purposes of this table, Performance Cash payments are assumed at target level. The value of unvested stock options, if accelerated upon a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">change-in-control</FONT></FONT> or termination, is&nbsp;determined using the excess, if any, of $203.88 (the closing price of ITW common stock on December&nbsp;31, 2020) over the option exercise price. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Messrs.&nbsp;Santi, O&#146;Herlihy, Martindale, and Hartnett met the retirement criteria for various grants under the Long-Term Incentive Plan during 2020. In case of
retirement, the 2018, 2019, and 2020 PSUs and Performance Cash awards would vest and be payable after the performance goals have been met. The unvested stock options continue to vest. In addition, 75&nbsp;percent of the 2020 stock option awards
would be forfeited since the assumed retirement would have occurred within one year from the grant date. The PSUs and Performance Cash awards would be <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rated</FONT> based on the retirement date. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Voluntary termination without good reason is not shown in the table because such a termination would not trigger the payment of severance benefits or accelerated vesting
of long-term awards. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Stock options, PSUs and Performance Cash awards, whether vested or unvested, are subject to forfeiture if the holder competes with, or divulges
confidential information about, the Company, or if the Compensation Committee determines that the holder engaged in gross misconduct or conduct that is against the business interests of the Company. Awards are also subject to forfeiture, in whole or
in part, in order to comply with applicable law, regulation, stock exchange rules, accounting rules, or our clawback policy. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">51 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Compensation Committee of the Board of Directors hereby
furnishes the following report to the stockholders of the Company in accordance with rules adopted by the Securities and Exchange Commission. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and
discussed with management the Compensation Discussion and Analysis contained in this proxy statement. Based on our review and discussions, we have recommended to the Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in
this proxy statement and the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2020. </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:24pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_31"></A>Pay Ratio </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="line-height:4.0pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:2pt;border-bottom:2.00pt solid #00416a">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><A NAME="rom_153919_79"></A>As required by
Section&nbsp;953(b) of the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, and Item 402(u) of Regulation <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">S-K,</FONT> we are providing the following information about the ratio of the annual total
compensation of the median ITW employee to the annual total compensation of our CEO. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The pay ratio reported below, in our view, is a reasonable estimate calculated
in a manner consistent with SEC rules, and is based on the methodologies and assumptions described below. SEC rules identifying the median employee and determining the pay ratio permit companies to employ a wide range of methodologies, estimates and
assumptions. As a result, the pay ratio reported by other companies, which may have utilized other permitted methodologies or assumptions, and which may have a significantly different workforce structure from ours, are likely not comparable to our
CEO pay ratio. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has an extensive global footprint in 52 countries and approximately 43,000 employees as of December&nbsp;31, 2020, of which approximately
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">two-thirds</FONT> are outside of the U.S. While compensation and benefits practices in these countries vary considerably, we commit to providing market competitive compensation and benefits, maintain fair labor
practices and ensure work environments that reflect our core values and culture everywhere we operate. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In many countries, ITW has small employee populations. We
therefore chose to apply the de minimis exemption, as permitted by the SEC, and excluded countries which, in the aggregate, make up under 5% of our total workforce. The countries excluded are as follows: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>

<TD WIDTH="70%"></TD>

<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="4%"></TD>
<TD></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#00416a" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Countries</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; padding-right:2pt"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Excluded Employees<BR>(in&nbsp;each country)</FONT></B></FONT></TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">
<TD VALIGN="top" STYLE="BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000; padding-left:8pt">Austria, Estonia, Guatemala, Indonesia, Luxembourg, Malta, Peru</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>

Emirates</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-LEFT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" NOWRAP STYLE="BORDER-RIGHT:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">Fewer&nbsp;than&nbsp;100&nbsp;employees</TD></TR>

</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To calculate the pay ratio, we identified the median employee based on our employee population as of October&nbsp;31, 2020, which was
approximately 43,000 employees, before excluding approximately 2,000 employees by applying the exemption noted above. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">54 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">To identify the median employee, we collected employees&#146; regular pay (salary or hourly wages), overtime pay and
shift differentials/premiums, and pay received for paid time off. We did not include annual incentives or bonuses, sales incentives or commissions, long-term cash or equity incentives, allowances, or any benefits received as part of a
company-sponsored defined benefit pension plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">With the information collected, we identified 21 employees whose compensation we believed to be around the median of
all employees, and then gathered other elements of compensation (variable pay, health and welfare, and retirement contributions) in order to determine the final median employee. In 2020, we determined a new median employee using this methodology.
</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our median employee compensation is $52,250. Total compensation, as set forth in the Summary Compensation Table, plus the Company costs to provide health and
welfare benefits for our CEO ($18,949) for 2020 is $14,026,305. Accordingly, the pay ratio between our CEO and median employee is 268:1. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">55 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_32"></A>Certain Relationships and Related Party Transactions
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We review related-party transactions in accordance with our Statement of Principles of Conduct, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and
Corporate Governance Guidelines, rather than a separate written policy. A related-party transaction is a transaction involving the Company and any of the following persons: a director, director nominee or executive officer of the Company; a holder
of more than 5% of ITW common stock; or an immediate family member or person sharing the household of any of these persons. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Statement of Principles of Conduct
states that our directors, officers and employees must avoid engaging in any activity, such as related-party transactions, that might create a conflict of interest or a perception of a conflict of interest. These individuals are required to raise
for consideration any proposed or actual transaction that they believe may create a conflict of interest. Our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> provide that no related-party transaction is void or voidable solely because a director has
an interest if (1)&nbsp;the material facts are disclosed to or known by the Board of Directors and the transaction is approved by the disinterested directors or an appropriate Board committee comprised of disinterested directors, (2)&nbsp;the
material facts are disclosed to or known by the stockholders and the transaction is approved by the stockholders, or (3)&nbsp;the transaction is fair to the Company as of the time it is approved. Our Corporate Governance Guidelines provide that the
Board will apply established Categorical Standards for Director Independence in making its independence determinations. Under the standards, certain relationships between the Company and a director would preclude a director from being considered
independent. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">On an annual basis, each director, director nominee and executive officer completes a Directors&#146; and Officers&#146; Questionnaire, which requires
disclosure of any transactions with the Company in which he or she, or any member of his or her immediate family, has a direct or indirect material interest. The Corporate Governance and Nominating Committee reviews the results of these
questionnaires and discusses any related-party transaction disclosed therein. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In addition, under its charter, the Audit Committee is responsible for reviewing,
approving, ratifying or disapproving all proposed related-party transactions that, if entered into, would be required to be disclosed under the rules and regulations of the SEC. In reviewing related-party transactions, the Audit Committee considers
the factors set forth in our Statement of Principles of Conduct, <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">by-laws</FONT> and Corporate Governance Guidelines, as well as other factors, including the Company&#146;s rationale for entering into the transaction,
alternatives to the transaction, whether the transaction is on terms at least as fair to the Company as would be the case were the transaction entered into with a third party, and the potential for an actual or apparent conflict of interest. No
member of the Audit Committee having an interest in a related-party transaction may participate in any decision regarding that transaction. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">56 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_33"></A>Audit Committee Report </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee of the Board of Directors is composed of four independent directors, as defined in the listing standards of the New York Stock Exchange, and the
Board of Directors has determined that all Audit Committee members are &#147;financially literate.&#148; In addition, the Board of Directors has determined that Messrs.&nbsp;Brutto and Henderson meet the Securities and Exchange Commission criteria
of &#147;audit committee financial expert.&#148; The Audit Committee operates under a written charter adopted by the Board of Directors, which was most recently reviewed by the Audit Committee in February 2021. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is responsible for providing oversight to the Company&#146;s financial reporting process through periodic meetings with ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accountants, internal auditors and management in order to review accounting, auditing, internal control and financial reporting matters. The Audit Committee is also responsible for assisting the Board in overseeing: (a)&nbsp;the
integrity of the Company&#146;s financial statements; (b)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s compliance with legal and regulatory requirements; (c)&nbsp;the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s qualifications, independence and performance;
(d)&nbsp;the Company&#146;s overall risk policies and practices; and (e)&nbsp;the performance of the Company&#146;s internal audit function. Company management is responsible for the preparation and integrity of the financial reporting information
and related systems of internal controls. The Audit Committee, in carrying out its role, relies on Company senior management, including senior financial management, and ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The following is the report of the Audit Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed
with senior management the audited financial statements of the Company. Management has confirmed to the Audit Committee that the financial statements have been prepared in conformity with generally accepted accounting principles. We have also
reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP, ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm, its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s financial statements. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with senior management their assertion and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. Management has confirmed to the Audit
Committee that internal controls over financial reporting have been appropriately designed and are operating effectively to prevent or detect any material financial statement misstatements. We have also reviewed and discussed with
Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP its audit and opinion regarding the Company&#146;s internal controls. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have reviewed and discussed with Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche
LLP the matters required to be discussed by the applicable requirements of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB) under which Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP must provide us with additional information regarding the scope and results
of its audit of the Company&#146;s financial statements. This information includes: (1)&nbsp;Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP&#146;s responsibility under generally accepted auditing standards; (2)&nbsp;significant accounting policies;
(3)&nbsp;management judgments and estimates; (4)&nbsp;any significant audit adjustments or internal control matters; (5)&nbsp;any disagreements with management; and (6)&nbsp;any difficulties encountered in performing the audit. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We have received from Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP a letter providing the disclosures required by applicable requirements of the PCAOB regarding the independent
accountant&#146;s communications with the Audit Committee concerning independence with respect to any relationships between Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP and the Company that in its professional judgment may reasonably be thought to bear on
independence. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has discussed its independence with us, and it has confirmed in the letter that, in its professional judgment, it is in a position to serve the Company as its Independent Registered Public Accounting
Firm. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">57 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee also discussed with the Company&#146;s internal auditors and independent registered public
accounting firm the overall scope and plans for their respective audits. The Audit Committee meets periodically with the internal auditors and independent registered public accounting firm, with and without management present, to discuss the results
of their examinations, their evaluations of the Company&#146;s internal controls, and the overall quality of the Company&#146;s financial reporting. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Based on the
reviews and discussions described above, we recommended to the Board of Directors, and the Board approved, the inclusion of the audited financial statements in the Company&#146;s Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for
the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2020, for filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:70%; text-indent:-2%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Pamela B. Strobel, Chair </P>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_34"></A>Proposal 2 - Ratification of the Appointment of
Independent </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Registered Public Accounting Firm </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee is directly responsible for the appointment, compensation, retention and oversight of the independent registered public accounting firm retained to
audit ITW&#146;s financial statements. The Audit Committee is also directly involved in the selection of the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s lead engagement partner in conjunction with the mandatory rotation of the lead
engagement partner. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has engaged Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP (Deloitte) to serve as ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm
for the fiscal year ending December&nbsp;31, 2021. Deloitte&nbsp;&amp; Touche LLP has been employed to perform this function for the Company since 2002. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Deloitte, the member firms of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu, and their respective affiliates (collectively, the Deloitte
Entities) will bill us approximately $10,386,000 for professional services in connection with the 2020 audit, as compared with $10,026,000 for the 2019 audit of the annual financial statements and internal controls. These fees relate to:
(i)&nbsp;the audit of the annual financial statements included in our Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K;</FONT> (ii)&nbsp;the review of the quarterly financial statements included in our Quarterly Reports on Form <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-Q;</FONT> (iii)&nbsp;the internal controls audit; and (iv)&nbsp;statutory audits. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit-Related Fees
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">During 2020 and 2019, the Deloitte Entities billed us approximately $45,000 and $130,000, respectively, for audit-related services. These fees relate
to work performed with respect to technical accounting assistance and comfort letters related to debt issuances. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Tax Fees
</I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">These fees include work performed by the Deloitte Entities for 2020 and 2019 with respect to tax compliance services such as assistance in preparing
various types of tax returns globally ($1,359,000 and $1,749,000, respectively) and tax planning services, often related to our restructurings and new tax rules ($931,000 and $729,000, respectively). </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>All Other Fees </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">There were no fees for
other services rendered by the Deloitte Entities for 2020 and 2019. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Audit Committee <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Pre-Approval</FONT>
Policies </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Audit Committee has adopted policies and procedures for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> of all audit and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related work to be performed by ITW&#146;s independent registered public accounting firm. As a part of those procedures, the Audit Committee performs a qualitative analysis of all audit and <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> work to be performed by our independent registered public accounting firm. Each year, the Audit Committee receives a detailed list of the types of audit-related and
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> related services to be performed, along with estimated fee amounts. The Audit Committee then reviews and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> audit work and certain categories of tax
and other <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services that may be performed. In conducting its analysis, the Audit Committee carefully contemplates the nature of the services to be provided and considers whether such services:
(i)&nbsp;are prohibited under applicable rules; (ii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants auditing their own work; (iii)&nbsp;would result in our accountants performing management functions; (iv)&nbsp;would place our accountants in a position of
acting as an advocate for the Company; or (v)&nbsp;would present a real risk of a conflict of interest or otherwise impair our accountants&#146; independence. The Audit Committee also annually <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approves</FONT> the
budget for annual GAAP, statutory and benefit </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">59 </P>

</DIV></Center>

plan audits. Company management provides quarterly updates to the Audit Committee regarding <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">year-to-date</FONT></FONT>
expenditures versus budget for audit and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-audit</FONT> services. The Audit Committee also considers whether specific projects or expenditures could potentially affect the independence of ITW&#146;s independent
registered public accounting firm. Company management and the independent registered public accounting firm will monitor the fees for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> services on an
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">on-going</FONT> basis to ensure that the <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approved</FONT> fees are not exceeded. Company management and the independent registered public accounting firm will seek <FONT

amounts. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Any new services and fees are presented to the Audit Committee for <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-approval</FONT> at each Audit Committee meeting. If

stockholders&#146; rejection and reconsider the appointment. Representatives of Deloitte will be present at our Annual Meeting and will have the opportunity to make a statement and respond to questions. </P>

<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_35"></A>Proposal 3 - Advisory Vote on Executive Compensation
</B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">In accordance with the recommendation by the Board and the preference expressed by our stockholders at the 2017 Annual Meeting, the Company has an
advisory vote on executive compensation annually. The Company is seeking your advisory vote on our executive compensation, as disclosed in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; section, the compensation tables and any related material
disclosed in this proxy statement pursuant to the SEC&#146;s compensation disclosure rules. The Compensation Committee will review the voting results and take them into consideration when making future decisions regarding executive compensation, but
because your vote is advisory, it will not be binding on the Compensation Committee, the Board or the Company. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We believe that our executive compensation program is
competitive and strongly aligned with our strategic performance goals and the long-term interests of our stockholders. Our compensation program and structure are more fully described in the &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#148; and
&#147;NEO Compensation&#148; sections of this proxy statement. We encourage you to closely review this information before voting on the compensation we paid to our NEOs in 2020. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">We ask our stockholders to approve, on an advisory basis, the compensation of our NEOs by voting &#147;FOR&#148; the following resolution: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:13%; margin-right:13%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><B>Resolved, </B>that the compensation of the named executive officers of Illinois Tool Works Inc. (the Company) as disclosed pursuant
to the compensation disclosure rules of the Securities and Exchange Commission under &#147;Compensation Discussion and Analysis,&#148; in the Summary Compensation Table, the related compensation tables and the related narrative disclosures in the
Company&#146;s proxy statement for its 2021 Annual Meeting, is hereby approved. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>The Board of Directors recommends a vote &#147;FOR&#148; the
approval of the compensation of </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>the Company&#146;s named executive officers. </B></P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">61 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><A NAME="rom53919_36"></A>Proposal 4 -
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Non-Binding</FONT> Stockholder Proposal to Permit </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:14pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Stockholders to Act by Written
Consent </B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company has been notified that John Chevedden, whose address is 2215 Nelson Avenue, Apt.&nbsp;205, Redondo Beach, California 90278, intends
to present the following proposal (the Stockholder Proposal) for consideration at the Annual Meeting. Mr.&nbsp;Chevedden has submitted documentation indicating that he is the beneficial owner of no less than 100 shares of the Company&#146;s common
stock. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">You should read carefully the description of the proposal. The Board of Directors recommends that you vote &#147;AGAINST&#148; the Stockholder Proposal. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Stockholder Proposal and Supporting Statement </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Proposal 4 &#150; Shareholder Right to Act by Written Consent </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Shareholders request that our board of directors take such steps as may be necessary to permit written consent by the shareholders entitled to cast the minimum number of
votes that would be necessary to authorize an action at a meeting at which all shareholders entitled to vote thereon were present and voting. This includes a shareholder ability to initiate any appropriate topic for written consent. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">This proposal topic won 95%-support at a Dover Corporation shareholder meeting and 88%-support at an AT&amp;T shareholder meeting. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Taking action by written consent in place of a meeting is a means shareholders can use to raise important matters outside the normal annual meeting cycle like the
election of a new director. Mr.&nbsp;Scott Santi received the most negative votes of any director in 2020. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">A shareholder right to act by written consent affords
Illinois Tool Works management strong protection for any status quo mentality during the current rapid changing business environment. Due to the low shareholder participation in annual meeting elections any action taken by written consent would
still need more than 62% supermajority approval from the shares that normally cast ballots at the ITW annual meeting to equal a majority from the ITW shares outstanding. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">A major advantage of special shareholder meetings, as an alternative to written consent, has been completely blown out of the water since the publication of the 2020 ITW
annual meeting proxy. A cornerstone of the 2020 ITW argument regarding written consent was that special shareholder meetings provide, &#147;an opportunity for all stockholders to be heard.&#148; </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">With the near universal use of tightly controlled online annual shareholder meetings, which can be only <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-minutes</FONT> of stilted
formalities, shareholders are severely restricted in engaging with management and making their views known because all challenging questions and comments management can be screened out by management. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For instance Goodyear management hit its mute button right in the middle of a formal shareholder proposal presentation at its 2020 shareholder meeting to bar
constructive shareholder criticism. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Plus AT&amp;T management would not allow any sponsors of shareholder proposals to even speak at the 2020 AT&amp;T online annual
meeting during the pandemic. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Please see: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><I>AT&amp;T investors denied a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">dial-in</FONT> as annual meeting goes online </I></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap"><FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">https://whbl.com/2020/04/17/att-investors-denied-a-dial-in-as-annual-meeting-goes-online/1007928/</FONT></FONT></FONT></FONT>
</FONT></FONT> </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">62 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p style="margin-top:1em; margin-bottom:0em; page-break-before:always">
<HR SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Another cornerstone of the 2020 ITW argument was that issues should be decided with notification to all stockholders.
This misplaced argument can lead to the conclusion that the chair of the ITW governance committee is ignorant of the fact that written consent can be structured so that all shareholders receive notice. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Now more than ever shareholders need to have the option to take action outside of a shareholder meeting since tightly controlled online shareholder meetings are a
shareholder engagement wasteland. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center">Please vote yes: </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>Shareholder Right to Act by Written Consent &#151; Proposal 4 </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:18pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:11pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B><I>Board of Directors Statement in Opposition </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Our Board recommends a vote AGAINST this proposal. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Our Board has carefully considered the Stockholder Proposal and believes the proposal is not in the best interests of the Company and our stockholders. The Board
therefore recommends a vote AGAINST the proposal. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#00416a"><B>Our Company has a track record of strong corporate governance. </B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">The Company is committed to sound corporate governance and has implemented numerous corporate governance policies and practices that ensure accountability of the Board
to our stockholders and provide our stockholders with greater access to the Board. As a result of these structural governance practices, stockholders have meaningful, year-round opportunities to bring important matters to the attention of the
Company, the Board and other stockholders, which we believe is the reason our stockholders considered and three times rejected the proponent&#146;s proposals for written consent &#151; in 2017, 2019 and 2020. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:9pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">For example: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:9pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
